<!-- Enables WinRM during the specialize pass, without a human ever
     logging in at the console: this is what actually lets the rest of
     the pipeline (the WinRM-reachability fallback in wait_for_callback,
     then run_post_install) run unattended, replacing what used to
     depend on a login triggering FirstLogonCommands.

     Deliberately touches only WinRM's own configuration, nothing under
     HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Winlogon: two
     different auto-logon mechanisms (the declarative <AutoLogon>
     element, and an earlier specialize-pass RunSynchronousCommand that
     wrote the exact same Winlogon registry values via reg.exe) each
     independently broke Setup outright with the same WINDEPLOY
     0x80220005 failure - different mechanisms, identical failure
     signature, which points at the Winlogon auto-logon registry state
     itself being what this specific Windows Server build's WINDEPLOY/
     OOBE launch chokes on here, not "any specialize-pass automation" in
     general (role installs, static IP, RDP, etc. all work fine from
     elsewhere in this pipeline without touching Winlogon at all). This
     is the next, deliberately different experiment: get WinRM up
     through a path that never sets AutoAdminLogon/DefaultUserName/
     DefaultPassword or anything else under that registry key at all.

     winrm.cmd (a WSH/VBScript wrapper, not a PowerShell cmdlet), not
     Enable-PSRemoting: the one specialize-pass attempt that used
     PowerShell here crashed Setup a third, different way ("the computer
     was unexpectedly restarted") before ever getting far enough to hit
     the Winlogon-shaped failure above, and there's no way to be certain
     in advance whether that was specifically a WMI/CIM-readiness issue
     (Microsoft Q&A 731439, a different cmdlet failing in
     RunSynchronousCommand for exactly that reason) or something more
     general about PowerShell's own startup this early - winrm.cmd is a
     much older, lighter, foundational component (present since Windows
     XP/2003) with none of PowerShell's engine/CLR/WMI-provider startup
     weight, the more conservative choice between the two either way.
     `-quiet` is documented as suppressing every confirmation prompt
     quickconfig would otherwise show interactively, essential here:
     anything that could block waiting for input Setup will never
     provide is worse than not running at all. netsh (a plain, native
     executable, matching the already-proven-reliable reg.exe pattern
     used elsewhere in specialize) opens the firewall explicitly too,
     redundant with quickconfig's own firewall step but cheap insurance
     given how much rides on this working.

     LocalAccountTokenFilterPolicy moves here too, when a custom admin
     account is configured: it used to be set by FirstLogonCommands
     (guest-side, needs a login), but WinRM authenticating as that
     account needs it regardless of which mechanism enabled WinRM
     itself, so it has to be set unconditionally here now rather than
     depending on a login that may never happen. _first_logon_commands.xml.j2
     still sets it too (redundant, harmless) for the case where a human
     does log in manually.

     Included into the single shared Microsoft-Windows-Deployment/
     RunSynchronous block in autounattend_base.xml.j2, alongside
     _specialize_install_vmware_tools.xml.j2 - kept as a separate file
     (not a separate <component>, unattend.xml's own schema doesn't
     clearly support more than one Microsoft-Windows-Deployment per
     pass) specifically so either one can be removed independently if it
     ever needs reverting, without touching the other. -->
<RunSynchronousCommand wcm:action="add">
    <Description>Start and configure the WinRM listener</Description>
    <Order>1</Order>
    <Path>cmd.exe /c winrm.cmd quickconfig -quiet</Path>
</RunSynchronousCommand>
<RunSynchronousCommand wcm:action="add">
    <Description>Open the firewall for WinRM</Description>
    <Order>2</Order>
    <Path>netsh.exe advfirewall firewall add rule name="DeployCore WinRM" dir=in action=allow protocol=TCP localport=5985</Path>
</RunSynchronousCommand>
{% if template.custom_admin_enabled %}
<RunSynchronousCommand wcm:action="add">
    <Description>Let a non-built-in local administrator authenticate over WinRM with a full token</Description>
    <Order>3</Order>
    <Path>reg.exe add "HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Policies\System" /v LocalAccountTokenFilterPolicy /t REG_DWORD /d 1 /f</Path>
</RunSynchronousCommand>
{% endif %}
